+4.144 KVM_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD
+--------------------------------
+
+:Capability: KVM_CAP_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD
+:Architectures: arm64
+:Type: vm ioctl
+:Parameters: struct kvm_arm_stage2_exec_guard (in)
+:Returns: 0 on success, < 0 on error
+
+This ioctl completes a page scan requested by
+``KVM_EXIT_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD``.  The capability must be enabled with
+``KVM_ENABLE_CAP`` before any vCPU is created.  Nested-virtualization vCPU
+features are rejected while it is enabled.
+
+::
+
+  struct kvm_arm_stage2_exec_guard {
+	__u64 gpa;
+	__u64 generation;
+	__u32 action;
+	__u32 flags;
+  };
+
+  #define KVM_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD_APPROVE_EXEC 0
+  #define KVM_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD_REJECT_EXEC  1
+
+``gpa`` and ``generation`` must exactly match the page and scan generation
+reported by an execute-guard exit; ``gpa`` must be page aligned and
+``generation`` must be nonzero.  The generation prevents a delayed response
+from approving a later scan or replacement backing at a reused GPA.  ``flags``
+must be zero.  ``APPROVE_EXEC`` changes a frozen page to executable/read-only
+after userspace has scanned its stable backing.  ``REJECT_EXEC`` returns it to
+writable/execute-never state.  Both actions invalidate the old stage-2 mapping
+before returning.  The ioctl returns ``EINVAL`` if the page is not currently
+frozen for that exact scan generation.
+
+With this capability enabled, missing per-page state means writable and
+execute-never.  An attempted execute freezes the page by synchronously
+unmapping it, then exits before the instruction executes:
+
+::
+
+  /* KVM_EXIT_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD */
+  struct {
+  #define KVM_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD_EXIT_EXEC    (1ULL << 0)
+  #define KVM_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD_EXIT_WRITE   (1ULL << 1)
+  #define KVM_ARM_STAGE2_EXEC_GUARD_EXIT_BLOCKED (1ULL << 2)
+	__u64 flags;
+	__u64 gpa;
+	__u64 generation;
+  } arm_stage2_exec_guard;
+
+``EXIT_EXEC`` asks userspace to scan the frozen page and issue this ioctl with
+the same nonzero ``generation``.
+More than one vCPU can report the same frozen page; userspace must serialize
+the single response.  Reads remain permitted while the scan is active.
+
+``EXIT_WRITE`` reports that a write was attempted against an approved
+executable/read-only page.  KVM has already revoked execute, changed the page
+to writable/execute-never, synchronously invalidated its mapping, and exited
+before the store; userspace may resume the vCPU without a response ioctl.
+When ``EXIT_BLOCKED`` is also set, the write raced an active scan and remains
+blocked until userspace approves or rejects that scan.
+
+KVM forces page-granular stage-2 mappings while the capability is enabled and
+discards all saved state for a memslot before replacing or deleting that
+slot.  MMU-notifier invalidation also discards approval before replacement
+backing can be mapped.  Thus a new backing page at a reused GFN starts
+writable/execute-never.
+Userspace is responsible for tracking approved pages in VM snapshots; a
+restored VM may conservatively leave every page writable/execute-never and
+rescan on its next execute request.
+
+The guard mediates guest CPU accesses through KVM stage-2.  Userspace must not
+give the VM aliased memslot backing, a DMA-capable assigned device, or another
+mapping that can modify an approved page without a guest stage-2 write fault.
+As with all KVM memory APIs, a VMM that directly modifies guest backing is
+trusted to revoke or discard the affected approval first.
+
+
